reviews.review_text: a big first According to those "in the know", this show hosted the first Wharf Rat meeting ever, and what a great show it apparently is!  apparently there are pictures, but we'll remain anonymous, thank you.

B+ show/A+audience recording Again, there never were any good recordings of this until this and the Charlie Miller soundboard source dropped.  This one has tremendous FOB and outdoor show presence; if you’re looking to not get disturbed in the early first set, this is not your row. It sounds like what the couple of photos I’ve found on-line reveal: that Heads on the field were on blankets, not on seats.  You can feel the rush to the front and at one point sigh with relief as the goon who busted his way into the area where the taper is like a bull in an FOB china closet says “it’s too loud” after twice saying “hey!” right into the mic during Rooster.  While he goes permanently to where the beer is and you think you might be able to settle down and groove, Bob Dylan comes out on stage and says “hold my unique interpretation of rhythm”.  Actually, he plays electric guitar, but does not sing on Rooster; the band rouses like the crowd upon his arrival and each member of the rhythm section performs a flourish like a Grateful Dead version of the wave.  In short, his presence kicks it up a notch at first but when he gets dialed in, it is revealed that he is largely playing a driving rhythm that is unrelated to what the Grateful Dead is doing at that moment.   It’s possible he’s not hearing them very well.  Several moments earlier in the set provide evidence of monitor problems: the disjointed starts to Alabama Getaway and Red Rooster that made it oddly difficult to identify these familiar set pieces.  This kind of starts a trend among Alabama Getaways that seems to coincide-perhaps just coincidentally-with the increasing rareness of the song’s appearance.  This would be the 14th-to-last version of Alabama Getaway, not out of the repertoire by ’86,  but a true late period rarity.  

The Baby Blue seems to be Jerry’s attempt to set the ship right after a truly disastrous	Don’t Think Twice that clearly had no rehearsal or previous discussion.  The attempt is not particularly successful however as Dylan attempts to perform backing vocals and co-lead vocals at once.  The Dead tell the crowd to “say bye” and so Dylan leaves and they keep it close to the ground with the next four.  Don’t Ease is pretty rollicking.  

Second set is the first true second set they do after the one-set show in Minneapolis on the Dylan part of the tour.  This trend thankfully continued for the rest of the tour.  This opens with an average China>Rider into a strong Playin’ that seems cut short when Bobby goes into Desolation Row.  Even today, the move seems crass  (Dylan fans had surely arrived by then), but it was undoubtably done b/c Jerry isn’t present and I assume was ill backstage. In any case, most hard core, superstitious fans of that period would probably be thinking “oh great.  Now Dylan won’t do it.”.  (Spoiler alert: Bob Dylan will not play Desolation Row that evening in Akron.) The rest of the show is fairly average until it somewhat falls apart near the end.  A B/B+ show overall.
